Covariance

\[{COV}_{xy} = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^N (x_i - \bar{x})(y_i - \bar{y})}{N-1}\]

mean.cijfers = mean(cijfers, na.rm=T)
mean.IQ      = mean(IQ,      na.rm=T)

delta.cijfers = cijfers - mean.cijfers
delta.IQ      = IQ      - mean.IQ

prod = (cijfers - mean.cijfers) * (IQ - mean.IQ)

covariance = sum(prod) / (N - 1)

Correlation

\[\frac{{COV}_{xy}}{S_xS_y}\]

correlation = covariance / ( sd(cijfers) * sd(IQ) ); correlation

Significance of a correlation

\[t_r = \frac{r \sqrt{N-2}}{\sqrt{1 - r^2}} \\ {df} = N - 2\]

df = N-2
df
## [1] 48
t.r = ( correlation*sqrt(df) ) / sqrt(1-correlation^2)
t.r
## [1] 6.50655

Viualize

One-sample t-test

if(!"visualize" %in% installed.packages()) { install.packages("visualize") }
library("visualize")

visualize.t(c(-t.r, t.r),df,section='tails')

Partial correlation

\[r_{xy \cdot z} = \frac{r_{xy} - r_{xz} r_{yz}}{\sqrt{(1 - r_{xz}^2)(1 - r_{yz}^2)}}\]

betrouwbaar = data$betrouwbaar

cor.cijfers.IQ            = cor(cijfers,IQ)
cor.cijfers.betrouwbaar   = cor(cijfers,betrouwbaar)
cor.IQ.betrouwbaar        = cor(IQ,betrouwbaar)

data.frame(cor.cijfers.IQ, cor.cijfers.betrouwbaar, cor.IQ.betrouwbaar)
##   cor.cijfers.IQ cor.cijfers.betrouwbaar cor.IQ.betrouwbaar
## 1       0.684577               0.3220983            0.33019

teller = cor.cijfers.IQ - (cor.cijfers.betrouwbaar * cor.IQ.betrouwbaar)
noemer = sqrt( (1-cor.cijfers.betrouwbaar^2)*(1-cor.IQ.betrouwbaar^2) )

partial.correlation = teller / noemer

partial.correlation
## [1] 0.6470647

Significance of parial correlation

df = N - 3

Regression

One predictor

Regression

\[y_i = b_0 + b_1 x_i + \epsilon_i\]

set.seed(28736)

N     = 123
mu    = 120
sigma = 15
IQ    = rnorm(N, mu, sigma)

b_0   =  1
b_1   = .04
error = rnorm(N, 0, 1)
  
cijfers = b_0 + b_1 * IQ + error

data = data.frame(cijfers, IQ)
data = round(data, 2)

# Write data for use in SPSS
write.table(data, "IQ.csv", row.names=FALSE, col.names=TRUE, dec='.')

The data

Calculate regression parameters

\[{cijfer}_i = b_0 + b_1 {IQ}_i + \epsilon_i\]

IQ      = data$IQ
cijfers = data$cijfers

Calculate \(b_1\)

\[b_1 = r_{xy} \frac{s_y}{s_x}\]

# Calculate b1

cor.cijfers.IQ = cor(cijfers,IQ)
sd.cijfers     = sd(cijfers)
sd.IQ          = sd(IQ)

b1 = cor.cijfers.IQ * ( sd.cijfers / sd.IQ )
b1
## [1] 0.04489104

Calculate \(b_0\)

\[b_0 = \bar{y} - b_1 \bar{x}\]

mean.cijfers = mean(cijfers)
mean.IQ      = mean(IQ)

b0 = mean.cijfers - b1 * mean.IQ

## [1] 0.4167131

Calculate t-values for b's

\[t_{n-p-1} = \frac{b - \mu_b}{{SE}_b}\]

Where \(n\) is the number of rows, \(p\) is the number of predictors, \(b\) is the beta coefficient and \({SE}_b\) its standard error.

# Get Standard error's for b
fit <- lm(cijfers~IQ)
se = summary(fit)[4]$coefficients[,2]

se.b0 = se[1]; se.b0
## (Intercept) 
##   0.8542378
se.b1 = se[2]; se.b1
##          IQ 
## 0.006998539

# Calculate t's
mu.b0 = 0
mu.b1 = 0
t.b0  = (b0 - mu.b0) / se.b0; t.b0
## (Intercept) 
##   0.4878187
t.b1  = (b1 - mu.b1) / se.b1; t.b1
##       IQ 
## 6.414345
n     = nrow(data) # number of rows
p     = 1          # number of predictors
df.b0 = n - p - 1
df.b1 = n - p - 1

Define regression equation

\[\widehat{cijfer} = {model} = b_0 + b_1 {IQ}\]

So now we can add the expected cijfers based on this model

data$expcijfers = b0 + b1 * IQ

Expected values

Let's have a look

\(y\) vs \(\hat{y}\)

And lets have a look at this relation between expectation and reality

expcijfers <- data$expcijfers

plot(expcijfers,cijfers, xlim = c(0,10), ylim = c(0,10))
lines(c(0,10), c(0,10), col='red')

Error

The error / residual is the difference between expected and reality

data$error = cijfers - expcijfers

Model fit

The fit of the model is the amount of error, which can be viewed in the correlation (\(r\)).

r = cor(expcijfers,cijfers)
r
## [1] 0.503735

Explained variance

r^2
## [1] 0.2537489

Explained variance visually

# This is all the cijfers data
plot(cijfers,xlab='participants')
# With the mean
lines(1:n,rep(mean(cijfers),n),col='blue',lwd=2)

# The blue lines are the total variance, the deviation from the mean.
segments(1:n, cijfers, 1:n, mean(cijfers), col='blue')

# The model predicts the cijfers scores
points(1:n,expcijfers, col='red')

# The part of the variation that overlaps is the 'explained' variance. 
segments(1:n, expcijfers, 1:n, mean(cijfers), col='red')

The part that does not overlap is therefore 'unexplained' variance. And because \(r^2\) is the explained variance, \(1 - r^2\) is the unexplained variance.

Test model fit

Compare model to mean Y (cijfers) as model

\[F = \frac{(n-p-1) r^2}{p (1-r^2)}\]

Where \({df}_{model} = n - p - 1 = N - K - 1\).

F = ( (n-p-1)*r^2 ) / ( p*(1-r^2) )
F
## [1] 41.14382

Signal to noise

Given the description of explained variance, F can again be seen as a proportion of explained to unexplained variance. Also known as a signal to noise ratio.

df.model = p # n = rows, p = predictors
df.error = n-p-1

SS_model = sum((expcijfers - mean(cijfers))^2)
SS_error = sum((cijfers - expcijfers)^2)
MS_model = SS_model / df.model
MS_error = SS_error / df.error
F = MS_model / MS_error 
F
## [1] 41.14382

SS_total = var(cijfers) * (n-1)
SS_total
## [1] 191.0732
SS_model
## [1] 48.48462
# Proportion explained variance
SS_model / SS_total
## [1] 0.2537489
r^2
## [1] 0.2537489

Visualize

visualize.f(F, df.model, df.error, section='upper')
